# Sedrah — Arabic Handwriting Stroke Generation

This repo fine-tunes a vision-language model to generate Arabic (and experimentally
Farsi) handwriting as a sequence of pen strokes, rather than just rendering text in a
font. Given a piece of text, the model outputs JSON describing each stroke's pen
trajectory (a list of `[x, y]` points per stroke), which can be rendered or replayed
as if a person were writing it.

See `PIPELINES.md` for detailed per-script usage and `pipeline.md` for a running log
of the exact commands used for each training run.

## Model

Base model: **`Qwen/Qwen2-VL-2B-Instruct`** (2.2B params), fine-tuned with **LoRA**
(via PEFT) on top of the frozen base — only the attention projections
(`q_proj`, `k_proj`, `v_proj`, `o_proj`) are adapted. Training code lives in
`code/training/train_sandbox.py` (single/multi-GPU via Accelerate) and
`code/training/train_distributed.py`.

Two input modes are supported:
- **Text-only**: `text -> stroke JSON`.
- **Multimodal (image + text)**: an image of the stroke trace is fed through
  Qwen2-VL's vision encoder alongside the text prompt, giving the model a visual
  reference for the target shape instead of generating blind. Wired in via
  `--image-manifest` in `train_sandbox.py`.

## Data

### Calliar (primary Arabic dataset)
[Calliar](https://github.com/ARBML/Calliar) is an academic online-handwriting
dataset of Arabic calligraphy: 2,500 sentence-level samples (2,000 train / 250
validation / 250 test). Each sample is a JSON list of strokes, one entry per
character/diacritic component, e.g. `{"ب": [[x,y], [x,y], ...]}`.
Lives at `sedrah_pipeline/calliar_dataset/json/`.

- `sedrah_pipeline/calliar_dataset/imgs/` — rendered images of each sample's actual
  stroke trace, used as the visual input for multimodal training.
- `sedrah_pipeline/calliar_dataset/pix2pix/` — two-panel reference images (writer's
  trace + a stylized calligraphy rendering); only the trace panel is used, to avoid
  teaching the model a misleading "should look like ornate font art" prior.

### Real Sedrah handwriting samples
`old_sedrah_pipeline/sandbox_data` contains 170 real handwriting samples in the same
JSON format. 131 of these turned out to be exact duplicates already present in
Calliar; the 39 unique ones were merged into the combined training set.

### POH-Db (Farsi, experimental)
[POH-Db](https://github.com/SLTLabAUT/POH-Db) — Persian Online Handwriting Database
(7,660 train / 782 validation / 864 test). Used for a from-base-model warm-up run
(`v5-farsi`) to test the pipeline on a second language before returning to Arabic.
Unlike Calliar, POH-Db has no per-character segmentation — every stroke in a sample
shares one label (the full line of text).
Lives at `sedrah_pipeline/poh_db_dataset/json/`.

### IAM-OnDB (English, prepared but not run)
A converter (`code/data_augmentation/convert_iam_ondb.py`) was written for the IAM
On-Line Handwriting Database (English), targeting the same JSON schema. The dataset
itself requires registration on the IAM website and was never actually downloaded
into this environment, so no English training run has happened yet.

## Augmented data

`code/data_augmentation/augment_calliar_trajectories.py` expands the Calliar set 5x
(2,500 -> 12,500 samples) by applying random geometric perturbations to each
sample's stroke coordinates:

- **Transforms**: scaling (±15%), rotation (±5°), shear (±0.2), Gaussian noise
  (std 0.8), and time-shift (when timing data is present).
- **0–3 transforms are stacked per copy**, chosen uniformly at random — about 25% of
  augmented copies are left clean (0 transforms, near-identical to the source) and
  the rest get a mix of distortions, so the model sees both faithful and noisy
  variants rather than uniformly-corrupted data.
- A manifest (`augmentation_manifest.jsonl`) records the exact transform(s) and
  parameters applied to every generated file, for traceability back to its source.

Because the augmented copies have transformed coordinates, the *original* stroke-trace
photos no longer match their shape. `code/data_augmentation/render_augmented_images.py`
re-renders a fresh image for every augmented sample directly from its (already
transformed) JSON, so multimodal training has an accurate image for both the original
and augmented data — current combined coverage is ~99.9% (14,982 / 15,000 samples).

The combined training set (`sedrah_pipeline/calliar_combined_dataset/`) merges the
original Calliar split with the full augmented set: **12,000 train / 1,500
validation / 1,500 test**.

## Example: local smoke test

```bash
python code/training/train_sandbox.py \
  --device mps \
  --max-train-samples 4 \
  --max-val-samples 1 \
  --epochs 1 \
  --batch-size 1 \
  --grad-accum-steps 2 \
  --max-length 2048 \
  --output-dir outputs/local-m4-fast-test
```
